event_investment_decisions.event_description:
In the upcoming MLB game, scheduled for September 17 at 7:40PM ET:
If the Los Angeles Angels win, the market will resolve to “Angels”.
If the Milwaukee Brewers win, the market will resolve to “Brewers”.
If the game is postponed, this market will remain open until the game has been completed.
If the game is canceled entirely, with no make-up game, this market will resolve 50-50.
To know when a postponed game will be played, please check the home team's schedule on MLB.com for the listed team and look for the game described as a makeup game.

decision.rationale: The market has already resolved correctly with Brewers winning the game. The price for Angels was 0.0355 which reflected their low chances of winning. Since we're analyzing this after the game is complete, there's no value in betting on this resolved market.

The Brewers won by 7 runs, easily covering the -1.5 spread. The market priced this at 0.85 which accurately reflected the high probability of this outcome. Since the market has already resolved correctly, there's no value in betting.

The total runs scored were 11 (9 by Brewers + 2 by Angels), which is clearly over 7.5. The market priced 'Over' at 0.82, which was a reasonable assessment of the high probability of this outcome. Since the market has already resolved correctly, there's no value in betting.

event_investment_decisions.event_description:
The FED interest rates are defined in this market by the upper bound of the target federal funds range. The decisions on the target federal fund range are made by the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meetings.

This market will resolve to the amount of basis points the upper bound of the target federal funds rate is changed by versus the level it was prior to the Federal Reserve's October 2025 meeting.

If the target federal funds rate is changed to a level not expressed in the displayed options, the change will be rounded up to the nearest 25 and will resolve to the relevant bracket. (e.g. if there's a cut/increase of 12.5 bps it will be considered to be 25 bps)

The resolution source for this market is the FOMC’s statement after its meeting scheduled for October 28 - 29, 2025 according to the official calendar: https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/fomccalendars.htm.

The level and change of the target federal funds rate is also published at the official website of the Federal Reserve at https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/openmarket.htm.

This market may resolve as soon as the FOMC’s statement for their October meeting with relevant data is issued. If no statement is released by the end date of the next scheduled meeting, this market will resolve to the "No change" bracket.

decision.rationale: The market is currently pricing in a 7.35% probability of a 50+ basis point rate cut in October 2025. Given that the Federal Reserve just implemented a 25 basis point cut in September and is signaling a gradual approach with two more cuts expected for 2025, a large 50+ basis point cut seems unlikely. The Fed has emphasized data dependence and caution in their approach. I estimate the true probability to be around 5%, making this market slightly overpriced.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 50+ bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The market is currently pricing in a 78.5% probability of a 25 basis point rate cut in October 2025. The Federal Reserve's recent statement and dot plot projections signal two more cuts in 2025, which would logically include the October meeting. Given the economic conditions with elevated inflation but labor market concerns, a 25 basis point cut aligns with the Fed's gradual approach. I estimate the true probability to be around 80%, making this market slightly underpriced.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 25 bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The market is currently pricing in a 14.5% probability of no change in interest rates after the October 2025 meeting. This is essentially the opposite of the 25 basis point cut market (market 553811). If that market has an 80% probability, then this market should have a 20% probability. The market appears to be underpricing the 'no change' scenario, possibly due to the Fed's recent signaling of additional cuts. I estimate the true probability to be around 20%.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: No change in Fed interest rates after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The market is currently pricing in a 0.75% probability of a 25+ basis point rate increase in October 2025. With the Federal Reserve having just implemented a rate cut and signaling more cuts ahead, a rate hike seems highly improbable. While inflation remains somewhat elevated, the Fed's focus appears to be on supporting the labor market rather than fighting inflation aggressively at this time. I estimate the true probability to be around 1%, making this market slightly underpriced.
